
[1]divulge

   DIVULGE, v.t. divulj. [L., to make public; the common people; people.]

   1. To make public; to tell or make known something before private or
   secret; to reveal; to disclose; as, to divulge the secret sentiments of
   a friend; to divulge the proceedings of the cabinet. Divulge is more
   generally applied to verbal disclosures, and publish to printed
   accounts. But they may be used synonymously. We may publish by words,
   and divulge by the press.

   2. To declare by a public act; to proclaim. [Unusual.]
